EXP4:-
👇
This program implements Peterson’s Algorithm to solve the critical section problem for two threads.

It uses two variables:
flag[2] → shows if a process wants to enter critical section
turn → decides whose turn it is
Each thread:
Sets its flag = 1 (wants to enter)
Gives turn to the other process
Waits if the other process also wants to enter
This ensures:
✅ Only one thread enters the critical section at a time (mutual exclusion)
✅ Avoids race condition on shared variable



EXP5:-
👇
This program implements the Banker’s Algorithm used in operating systems for deadlock avoidance.

It takes:
Allocation matrix
Max matrix
Available resources
Then calculates:
Need = Max − Allocation

Logic:
Check if a process’s need ≤ available resources
If yes → execute it, release its resources
Add it to safe sequence
Repeat for all processes
If all processes execute → Safe State
If not → Unsafe State (possible deadlock)
👉 In short:
It checks whether the system can execute all processes safely without causing deadlock and gives a safe sequence.

