🔹 Core Idea

This program compares 3 Page Replacement Algorithms used in Operating Systems:

FIFO
LRU
Optimal

👉 Goal: Minimize page faults (when a required page is not in memory)

🔹 1. FIFO (First In First Out)
Uses queue
Oldest page is removed first

Logic:

If page not in memory → page fault
If memory full → remove front (oldest)
Insert new page

👉 Simple but not always efficient

🔹 2. LRU (Least Recently Used)
Uses vector (queue style)
Removes the least recently used page

Logic:

If page found → move it to end (recently used)
If not found:
Remove front (least used) if full
Insert new page

👉 Better than FIFO (uses recent usage)

🔹 3. Optimal
Uses future knowledge (best possible)

Logic:

If page not present:
If space → insert
Else:
Replace page used farthest in future
If a page is never used again → replace it

👉 Gives minimum possible page faults

🔹 Key Difference
Algorithm	Replacement Rule
FIFO	Oldest page
LRU	Least recently used
Optimal	Used farthest in future
🔹 In Short

👉 The program:

Simulates memory with fixed frames
Checks each page request
Counts page faults for each algorithm

 
